  "prompt": "How do you stop a sunburn from peeling?",
  "response": "Unfortunately, once the damage is done and your skin is starting to peel from a sunburn, you can't completely stop it. Peeling is your body's way of shedding the damaged skin. However, you can minimize the peeling and help your skin heal as comfortably and quickly as possible. Here's what you should do:\n\n**Key Steps to Minimize Peeling and Promote Healing:**\n\n*   **Stay Hydrated:** Drink plenty of water to help your skin heal from the inside out.\n\n*   **Moisturize, Moisturize, Moisturize!:** This is the most important step. Apply a thick, fragrance-free, hypoallergenic moisturizer liberally and often throughout the day. Look for ingredients like:\n    *   **Aloe vera:** Soothes and hydrates.\n    *   **Hyaluronic acid:** Helps skin retain moisture.\n    *   **Ceramides:** Help repair the skin barrier.\n    *   **Shea butter:** Emollient and moisturizing.\n    *   **Avoid products with alcohol, fragrances, and dyes**, as these can further irritate the skin.\n\n*   **Cool Compresses:** Apply cool, damp compresses to the affected areas for 10-15 minutes several times a day. This can help soothe the skin and reduce inflammation.\n\n*   **Avoid Irritation:**\n    *   **Don't pick or peel at the skin.** This can lead to infection and scarring. Let the skin come off on its own.\n    *   **Wear loose-fitting, breathable clothing** made of cotton or other soft materials. Avoid tight or scratchy fabrics.\n    *   **Avoid harsh soaps and detergents.** Use a gentle, moisturizing cleanser.\n\n*   **Protect from Further Sun Exposure:**\n    *   **Stay out of the sun as much as possible** until the sunburn has completely healed.\n    *   **If you must go outside, wear protective clothing** (long sleeves, pants, a wide-brimmed hat) and apply a broad-spectrum sunscreen with an SPF of 30 or higher to any exposed skin.\n\n*   **Consider Over-the-Counter Medications (if needed):**\n    *   **Pain relievers:** Over-the-counter pain relievers like ibuprofen (Advil, Motrin) or naproxen (Aleve) can help reduce pain and inflammation.\n    *   **Hydrocortisone cream:** A mild (1%) hydrocortisone cream can help reduce itching and inflammation. Use sparingly and for a limited time, as prolonged use can thin the skin.\n\n**What *NOT* to Do:**\n\n*   **Don't Exfoliate:** Avoid using scrubs, loofahs, or other exfoliating products on sunburned skin.\n*   **Don't Use Products with Harsh Chemicals:** Avoid products containing alcohol, fragrances, or dyes, as these can further irritate the skin.\n*   **Don't Ignore Signs of Infection:** If you notice signs of infection, such as increased pain, redness, swelling, pus, or fever, see a doctor right away.\n\n**When to See a Doctor:**\n\n*   Severe sunburn with blisters covering a large area.\n*   Fever, chills, nausea, or vomiting.\n*   Signs of infection (increased pain, redness, swelling, pus).\n*   Confusion or dizziness.\n*   Dehydration (extreme thirst, decreased urination).\n\n**In summary, while you can't stop the peeling entirely, consistent and diligent moisturizing, gentle care, and protection from further sun exposure will help minimize the peeling, relieve discomfort, and promote faster healing.**  Prevention is always the best strategy, so always wear sunscreen, seek shade, and wear protective clothing when spending time in the sun.\n",
